#Text=Bridget Anne Kelly
#Text=For the American singer , see Bridget Kelly .
#Text=Bridget Anne Kelly is the former Deputy Chief of Staff to the Governor of New Jersey Chris Christie .
#Text=Kelly , a New Jersey native , grew up in Ramsey and graduated from Immaculate Heart Academy in 1990 . [ 1 ]
#Text=She graduated from Mount St. Mary 's University in 1994 with a bachelor of arts degree in political science . [ 2 ]
#Text=Career
#Text=Kelly began her government career by working as a legislative aide to Assemblyman David C. Russo , later becoming Russo 's chief of staff . [ 2 ] [ 3 ] [ 4 ]
#Text=In 2010 , Kelly became Director of Legislative Relations under Governor Chris Christie .
#Text=In April 2013 , Christie appointed her to be his Deputy Chief of Staff .
#Text=On November 4 , 2016 , Kelly was convicted for her involvement in the " Bridgegate " affair . [ 5 ] [ 6 ]

column1: #Text=She was sentenced to 18 months imprisonment ( later reduced to 13 months ) on March 29 , 2017 . [ 7 ] [ 8 ] [ 9 ]
#Text=Fort Lee lane closure scandal
#Text=Main article : Fort Lee lane closure scandal

#Text=On November 4 , 2016 , Kelly was found guilty in connection with the four-day closures of entrance ramps to the George Washington Bridge in the late summer of 2013 , in part of what has been described as politically motivated retribution against the mayor of Fort Lee , New Jersey . [ 10 ]

#Text=On August 13 , 2013 , Kelly sent an eight-word e-mail to David Wildstein , a Christie appointee to the board of commissioners of the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey , that read , " Time for some traffic problems in Fort Lee .

column1: #Text=The bigger problem is getting kids to school .
#Text=Please help .
#Text=It 's maddening .

#Text=On January 9 , 2014 , after the emails were disclosed , the governor announced that he had fired Kelly , calling her action " stupid " and " deceitful " and claiming her actions had caused him to mislead the public . [ 13 ]

#Text=That day , Kelly was named as a defendant in a federal class action lawsuit in the U.S. District Court for the District of New Jersey that cited a civil conspiracy and " willful , wanton , arbitrary , and egregious official misconduct " . [ 14 ] [ 15 ]

#Text=In the wake of her firing , police established no parking zones outside of Kelly 's home in Ramsey to keep press and gawkers away , while " no trespassing " signs were placed on the lawn of the home . [ 16 ]

#Text=When she received subpoenas for documents from the New Jersey legislative committee , Kelly 's attorneys indicated she would not comply with the subpoenas , citing their clients ' Fifth Amendment right against self-incrimination and Fourth Amendment right against unreasonable search and seizure [ 17 ] [ 18 ]
#Text=The committee voted to compel Kelly to produce the previously requested documents , instructing special counsel Reid Schar to " take all necessary steps " to enforce them . [ 19 ]
#Text=But Superior Court Judge Mary Jacobson found no basis to force Kelly and Bill Stepien , the governor 's two-time campaign manager , to comply with the subpoenas .
#Text=The pair had objected to the requests , issued in January , asserting that being forced to identify and turn over records would violate their Fifth Amendment rights against self-incrimination .
#Text=They called the committee 's requests a fishing expedition .
#Text=The Court agreed . [ 20 ]
#Text=On May 1 , 2015 , Kelly was indicted on nine charges in connection with her involvement in the scandal . [ 21 ]
#Text=She pleaded not guilty .
#Text=Courts have ruled that evidence provided in discovery by the US Attorney cannot be made public .
#Text=Courts also ruled that all materials used to prepare the so-called Mastro Report which exonerated the Christie administration must be turned over to the defense . [ 22 ]
#Text=The state has denied Kelly 's request for reimbursement of legal fees . [ 23 ]
#Text=Conviction
#Text=On November 4 , 2016 , the jury in the " Bridgegate " trial returned guilty verdicts on all counts against Bridget Kelly and co-defendant Bill Baroni . [ 24 ] [ 25 ]
#Text=On March 29 , 2017 , U.S. District Judge Susan D. Wigenton sentenced Kelly to 18 months in prison and 500 hours of community service . [ 26 ] [ 27 ] [ 28 ]

#Text=On November 27 , 2018 , the Third Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the majority of the convictions , overturning the determination that Kelly and Baroni had violated the civil rights of travelers , finding there is no established civil right to interstate travel giving rise to a criminal conviction . [ 29 ]
#Text=The court directed that Kelly and Baroni be re-sentenced on the remaining seven counts of the indictment . [ 30 ]
#Text=On April 24 , 2019 , Kelly was sentenced to 13 months in federal prison for her role in the George Washington Bridge scandal .
#Text=Kelly was originally sentenced to 18 months ; it was reduced to 13 months after a federal appeals court tossed out some of her charges . [ 31 ]
#Text=On June 28 , 2019 the United States Supreme Court agreed to take up her case ; her prison sentence was delayed pending its ruling .

#Text=Political and legal commentators have noted this action by the Court as part of a continuingly " more stringent definition of the law " governing corruption cases involving political malfeasance . [ 32 ]
#Text=Kelly is a divorced mother with four . [ 33 ] [ 34 ] [ 2 ]
